article.headline: Lady Vols win third straight game
article.linkText: First-half surge helps Tennessee spank TCU
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Lady Vols have another point guard, and coach Pat Summitt is loving it.

Shyra Ely scored 23 points and freshman point guard Sa'de Wiley-Gatewood hit three 3-pointers in her collegiate debut, leading Tennessee (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) to an 82-55 victory over TCU on Sunday.

Starting point guard Alexis Hornbuckle added 15 points, while Shanna Zolman had 11 and Brittany Jackson 10 for the Lady Vols (7-2), who have won three straight since losing to No. 3 Duke earlier this month.

Wiley-Gatewood and Hornbuckle -- both high school All-Americas -- were put in charge of Tennessee's offense in place of senior Loree Moore, who had her tonsils out this month and is expected to be out a few more weeks.

Wiley-Gatewood missed the first six games because of patellar tendinitis and the last two games for breaking team rules.

Now Summitt has two good passers, scorers and defensive stoppers that both need plenty of minutes on the court.

"It's the best problem I've had all year. I'll figure it out," Summitt said.

Tennessee's offense looked remarkably different from the team that struggled to score earlier this season.

"I think Sa'de Gatewood is a great addition," Summitt said. "Her awareness and passing skills are obviously going to make us a better half-court team as well as a transition team."

Sandora Irvin, who became the all-time leading scorer for the Lady Frogs (7-4) last week, had 21 points and 16 rebounds.

TCU fell out of the Top 25 after losing at Arkansas State and Utah and is still looking for its first road win of the season. The Lady Frogs are 0-4 against Tennessee.

"We probably played 20 minutes of decent basketball," TCU coach Jeff Mittie said.

Hornbuckle started and also had six assists and five steals.

Wiley-Gatewood came off the bench to score nine points -- all on the 3-pointers -- and had four assists and four steals.

At times, they were both on the court.

Both point guards took pressure off some of the other players Tennessee relies on to score.

"Did you see my shooting percentage?" Ely said when asked about the impact of the guards. "They're great."

Ely was 9-of-12 from the field in her best offensive output of the season.

The Lady Vols pulled away in the first half. The teams traded the lead six times before halftime with 22-21 being TCU's last lead with 8:55 remaining.

Summitt immediately called a timeout, and the Lady Vols responded by outscoring the Lady Frogs 27-9 the rest of the way and led by as many as 19 during their run.

Wiley-Gatewood showed off her passing and shooting skills during the spurt.

She hit two 3-pointers and had some no-look passes that jazzed up Tennessee's offense.

Wiley-Gatewood drove into the lane and passed to a cutting Dominique Redding for an easy basket.

Not to be outdone, Hornbuckle also showed some flash.

Jackson got a steal but missed the layup at the other end. Hornbuckle got the rebound and passed the ball behind her back to Jackson. She missed, but the partisan crowd roared in appreciation of the effort.

Tennessee led 48-31 at halftime, the most points the Lady Vols had scored in the first half this season.

The Lady Frogs had 32 turnovers, including 19 steals by Tennessee. The Lady Vols had 22 turnovers.
